Paul Barreira, professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the University, said that the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students were deprived of severe sleep during the week.
The course, one hour duration, includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, dolls and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how it affects sports performance to lack sleep, and about the importance of maintaining a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Next, a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that student behavior will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes," said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride of staying awake all night still exists, he said, and he added that modern technology and growing pressure that students suffer makes sleep deprivation an increasing problem.
Making sure to enjoy a good quality sleep for enough time should be a "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, tiredness and anxiety, added, even to avoid getting weighty, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in ininsanity mode and makes students always hungry.
