The latest report by Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of proliferation are being reported more widespread in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which suggests a lower concentration.
The proliferation of the red tide extends along 200 km of coast, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
You can find stains 16 km from Hillsborough County Coast, but in less places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Easter County.
Average concentrations on the coast or at a distance from the coast to the county of Pinellas have been reported over the past week, concentrations of downs and ups and downs on the coast to Hillsborough County, concentrations of background or ups in Manatee County, concentrations of middles and middles in Charlotte County, concentrations of bottoms and ups on the coast or aways of Lee County and lows in Collier County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported to the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
